Principal highways: Hylan Blvd., Richmond Rd. There were many foreclosures here. As a general rule thje 2-family units were better built than the singles. Supplemental Information: Sales Prices (Dec.1940): Higher priced singles have come down sharply where any sales at all are noted; the house quoted at $7000 in 1938 may be offered at $5500 today. Two family structures have suffered even more; whereas $8500 to $12,000 was mentioned as a fair bracket in 1938, today it would be more like $6000 to $8500, with no demand whatever at the second figure. Rental Prices (Dec.1940): Rents were always pretty low in here, considering property values, and therefore haven't changed noticeably within the past two years. Singles still bring from $20 to $45; apartments in two family dwellings from $40 to $45 heated. Demand is good and there appear to be very few vacancies. General Comments: HOLC has upwards of 40 houses in this area. Many were early foreclosures and have not been reappraised, consequently are priced somewhat higher than competing houses. Few offers are made on property in this area. Property management brokers operating in this area cite instances where the Corporation refused offers two months ago which they are now seeking to revive. Competitors are not selling well in here either; although they have a heavy load at present. Majority of sales are to Italians, who buy sacrifice property in wife's name. No new construction has gone in during the past year and the area is noticeably "stagnant", probably because of the racial factor. Institutions have made consecutive reductions of their offerings without apparently having much effect on speeding up liquidation. No future improvement forecast and the trend is downward. Typical Sales: |Address|Type|Price&Terms|Remarks| (
