Principal highway: Amboy Rd. These are 3 of the oldest villages on Staten Island. Very little change is noted here, with the old native element still in the majority. Supplemental Information: Sales Prices (Dec. 1940): A negligible sales demand and consequent lack of activity have resulted in little or no change in prices for single houses, of which the area is entirely comprised. Today's range approximates that of 1939: $3500 to $5500. A few small new cottages have been sold in here for prices ranging in $2500 class, but these are exceptional and not at all consistent with the balance of the area. Rental Prices (Dec. 1940): Same as for 1938-39; sinlges renting for $30 to $45 and not much activity very little seasonal movement in this district is too rural in character. Very few vacancies observed in a tour of the area. General Comments: Some new construction in here recently: 14 small 4 to 5 room bungalows just south of Amboy Road in the small detached section of C-23. These were built by a Brooklyn concern and trouble was experienced even before completion, with the sanitation. The land is low at that point and drainage is insufficient. The condition was so bad that the Sanitary Department refused to issue certificates of occupancy for these houses. They were sold at various prices with this defect, probably $2500 being the top price, and are now all occupied. In general the area is best north of Amboy Road, though even here poor houses are scattered among the better ones. The three "stems" extending northward in this area are all very sparsely developed, perhaps about 20 to 30%. Much of the area was cut through with streets and sidewalks years ago in the hope of future growth which never came. This is particularly true of the eastern most "finger", along Hugenot Avenue, where there are only two streets with houses: Rathbun and Rensselaer (north of Edgegrove). The street surface in here is very bad on all side streets: sidewalks are partially overgrown with small trees and brush. Three new bungalows with built in garages on Ramona Avenue, a brand new dual highway which opens up some good building sites in this area. HOLC has 15 houses in the area; institutions have an estimated 50 at the most. Sales have been rarae. (None for HOLC). Approval of the new dry dock site in Prince's Bay should make a tremendous difference here. Typical Sales (
