Principal highways: Amboy Rd., Hyland Ave., Main St. Many foreclosures in this section. Old native element still dominating. Most of the residents were employed in factories across the river in New Jersey with the partial shut down of many of these. Stagnation is apparent in Tottenville. Supplemental Information: Sales Prices (Dec.1940): Prices on properties which were quoted at $7000 in 1938-39 have dropped about 10% or more. Approaching the bottom of the range for singles, the price drop becomes progressively less, 5% being the average loss in value for the smaller houses in the $2500 class. Two family structures are at an absolute minimum of demand and few indeed are sales of this type. Prices would be arbitrary and are not even suggested, as sellers will take almost anything they can get in forced sales of this kind. Rental Prices (Dec.1940): Rents were low here in 1939 and have not regained any of the drop which followed the industrial decline in Tottenville about 1930. The village is too far removed from the New York ferry and there are no local opportunities for employment. Transportation via the Outerbridge Crossing to nearby New Jersey is expensive, and those who are employed in Jersey factories prefer to live on that side of the river (Arthur Kill). Prices today would be no different than they were two years ago, i.e. $22 to $45 for singles; $25 to $45 for two family units. General Comments: Attractions are away from Tottenville rather than to it. Some houses are standing vacant because it is difficult to find tenants because of the distance to the New York ferry, and the cost of getting there (25 cents). This was a fairly thriving town when the shipyards were operating, but with their closing in 1930 came a decline. There is very little activity here today. HOLC holds some 36 houses unsold and institutions have an estimated 75 more. As stated, sales have been very few. HOLC sold only one during 1940. Here again, great activity would probably result from the approval of the proposed Prince's Bay drydock site, which is now under consideration. Typical Sales: |Address|Type|Price&Terms|Remarks| (
